message.content: No, the authors do not include theoretical results in the methods section provided. The section focuses on presenting and defining concepts, describing the understandability-completeness trade-off, and introducing the utility metric for evaluating explainability methods.

No, the authors do not state the full set of assumptions for all theoretical results in this methods section. They provide an outline of their approach and introduce their proposed usefulness metric along with the utility scores in a human-centered evaluation framework. The assumptions regarding the participants, training samples, and other factors that might influence their theoretical framework are not explicitly stated.

No. The authors do not present any explicit theoretical results in this methods section. They primarily focus on introducing the meta-predictor framework and describing the details of their approach, including the understandability-completeness trade-off and the usefulness metric.
